{"Title":"ObjectCloud:  Developer Documentation","Contents":"<p>ObjectCloud contains a rich development API. The entire API is available through REST, and is automatically wrapped in Javascript for effortless development of rich in-browser applications. In addition, the same API is available in server-side Javascript for&#160;security&#160;and performance-sensitive operations.</p><h1>Examples</h1><p>Examples of built-in ObjectCloud applications and how they use ObjectCloud's APIs.</p><h1>Adding File Types to ObjectCloud</h1><p>Core to <a xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\" href=\"/Docs/add file type.page\">ObjectCloud's flexibility is the ability to add additional programmer-defined file types</a>.</p><h1>API</h1><p><a xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\" href=\"/Docs/API.page\">ObjectCloud's API</a>&#160;is rich and powerful.</p><h1>Server-Side Javascript</h1><p><a xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\" href=\"/Docs/server side JS.page\">Server-side Javascript</a>&#160;is useful when chaining many API calls that would run slowly in the browser, or for performing operations that can not be performed&#160;securely&#160;within the browser.</p><h1>Contributing</h1><p>Interested in contributing? Send an email to gwbasic - at - appfeeds - dot - com. At this time, all contributions must have copyright assigned to Andrew Rondeau unless prior arrangements are made.</p><p></p><h1>Specifications</h1><p><a xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\" href=\"/Docs/Specs\">Specifications on how ObjectCloud works are online</a>.</p><h1>Deprecated Guides</h1><p><a xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\" href=\"/Docs/webcomponents.page\">WebComponents</a>: A component system used prior to ObjectCloud's templating system. There are still a few pages which rely on the WebComponent system, although they will be ported to the templating system as part of routine&#160;maintenance.</p><p><a xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\" href=\"/Docs/Mixing Server Side JS and HTML.page\">Mixing Server Side Javascript and HTML</a>: &#160;An older system that used server-side Javascript to render web pages. It relied on the WebComponent system. Pages that are based on this system will be ported to the templating system as part of routine&#160;maintenance.</p><p></p><h1><span class=\"Apple-style-span\" style=\"font-weight: normal; font-size: medium; \"><a xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\" href=\"http://10.0.1.198:1080/Docs/simple%20storage%20walkthrough.page\">Simple storage with just a POST form</a></span><span class=\"Apple-style-span\" style=\"font-weight: normal; font-size: medium; \">: A walkthrough for persisting data without using any coding whatsoever.</span></h1><div><span class=\"Apple-style-span\" style=\"font-weight: normal; font-size: medium; \"><meta charset=\"utf-8\"/><h1><span class=\"Apple-style-span\" style=\"font-weight: normal; font-size: medium; \">These walkthroughs are for old sample applications that used the WebComponent system.</span></h1></span><ul><li><a xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\" href=\"http://10.0.1.198:1080/Docs/Review%20Voting%20Booth.page\">Inspect the voting booth's source code</a></li><li><a xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\" href=\"http://10.0.1.198:1080/Docs/review%20blog.page\">Inspect the blogum's source code</a></li></ul><p></p></div><p></p>"}